Nigidius said that under (south of) * the zodiacal sign Virgo there was a constellation having the figure of a ploughman and the name of Horos. On the celestial globe of the Greeks this constellation did not exist ; but the figure of a ploughman stands in this place, under (south of) Virgo, on a relies in the temple of Hathor at Denderah (Boll sph. tas. 111). It was a constellation on the celestial globe of the Egyptians. sphaera barbarica means a plan of the heavens, especially an Egyptian 01· Chaldaean plan, which groups the stars into constellations other than the Greek.† This appears from the examples of the term collected by Boll sph. pp. 350—66, whence I take the following.
